PART A: Core Concepts & Definitions (Q1–Q30) 
Q: 1. What is JavaScript? 
A: JavaScript is a lightweight, interpreted, single-threaded scripting language used to make web pages 
interactive. It supports OOP, functional, and event-driven programming. 
Q: 2. What is the difference between var, let, and const? 
A: var: function-scoped, hoisted (undefined). let: block-scoped, not hoisted (TDZ). const: block-scoped, 
must be initialized, cannot be reassigned. 
Q: 3. What is hoisting? 
A: Hoisting is JS's default behavior of moving declarations to the top of their scope before execution. 
var declarations are hoisted (as undefined), function declarations are fully hoisted. let/const are hoisted 
but stay in Temporal Dead Zone. 
Q: 4. What is a closure? 
A: A closure is a function that remembers its outer lexical scope even when executed outside that 
scope. Used for data privacy, memoization, and factory functions. 
Q: 5. What is the event loop? 
A: The event loop continuously checks the call stack and callback queue. When the stack is empty, it 
pushes callbacks from the queue. It's what makes JS asynchronous despite being single-threaded. 
Q: 6. What is a Promise? 
A: A Promise represents a future value. It has 3 states: pending, fulfilled, rejected. Chained with 
.then()/.catch()/.finally(). Avoids callback hell. 
Q: 7. What is async/await? 
A: Syntactic sugar over Promises. async function returns a Promise. await pauses execution until 
Promise resolves. Makes async code look synchronous. 
Q: 8. Difference between == and ===? 
A: == does type coercion before comparison. === checks both value AND type without coercion. 
Always prefer === for predictable behavior. 
Q: 9. What is the 'this' keyword? 
A: this refers to the object that calls the function. In global scope: window (browser). In object method: 
the object. Arrow functions don't have their own this—they inherit from parent scope. 
Q: 10. What are arrow functions? 
A: Arrow functions are a shorter syntax: (params) => expression. They don't have their own this, 
arguments, super. Cannot be used as constructors. 
Q: 11. What is prototypal inheritance? 
A: Objects in JS inherit from other objects via __proto__ chain. When a property isn't found, JS walks 
up the prototype chain until null. 
Q: 12. What is the difference between null and undefined? 
A: undefined: variable declared but not assigned. null: intentional absence of value (must be explicitly 
set). typeof null === 'object' (JS bug). 
Q: 13. What is event delegation? 
A: Instead of adding event listeners to every child, add one to the parent. Uses event bubbling. Efficient 
for dynamic elements: parent.addEventListener('click', e => { if(e.target.matches('.btn')) ... }) 
Q: 14. What is debouncing? 
A: Debouncing delays function execution until after a wait time since the last call. Used for search 
input, window resize. Example: clearTimeout(timer); timer = setTimeout(fn, delay) 
Q: 15. What is throttling? 
A: Throttling ensures a function runs at most once every N milliseconds. Used for scroll/mousemove 
events. Maintains regular execution rate unlike debounce. 
Q: 16. What is the spread operator? 
A: ... operator spreads iterable elements. Used for: [...arr1, ...arr2] (merge arrays), {...obj1, ...obj2} 
(merge objects), function calls: fn(...args) 
Q: 17. What is destructuring? 
A: Extract values from arrays/objects: const {name, age} = person; const [first, ...rest] = arr; Can have 
defaults: const {x = 0} = obj; 
Q: 18. What are template literals? 
A: Backtick strings: `Hello ${name}`. Support multi-line strings, expression interpolation, tagged 
templates. Much cleaner than string concatenation. 
Q: 19. What is a generator function? 
A: function* gen() { yield 1; yield 2; } Returns iterator. Pauses at each yield. Used for lazy evaluation, 
infinite sequences, async flow control. 
Q: 20. What is Symbol? 
A: Symbol() creates unique primitive value. Used as object property keys to avoid naming conflicts. 
Symbol('id') !== Symbol('id') always. 
Q: 21. What is WeakMap/WeakSet? 
A: WeakMap: keys must be objects, doesn't prevent GC. WeakSet: only objects, no iteration. Used for 
private data, caching without memory leaks. 
Q: 22. What is Object.freeze() vs Object.seal()? 
A: freeze(): can't add/remove/modify properties. seal(): can't add/remove but CAN modify existing 
values. Both are shallow. 
Q: 23. What is the difference between call, apply, bind? 
A: call(ctx, a, b): invokes immediately with individual args. apply(ctx, [a,b]): invokes with array. 
bind(ctx): returns new function with fixed this. 
Q: 24. What is memoization? 
A: Caching function results for repeated inputs. function memoize(fn) { const cache = {}; return (x) => 
cache[x] || (cache[x] = fn(x)); } 
Q: 25. What is currying? 
A: Transforming f(a,b,c) into f(a)(b)(c). const add = a => b => a + b; add(2)(3) === 5. Used for partial 
application. 
Q: 26. What is the Temporal Dead Zone (TDZ)? 
A: Period between entering scope and let/const declaration. Accessing variable in TDZ throws 
ReferenceError. Prevents use-before-declare bugs. 
Q: 27. What are Proxy and Reflect? 
A: Proxy wraps object to intercept operations: new Proxy(target, {get(t,k){...}, set(t,k,v){...}}). Reflect 
provides methods for interceptable operations. 
Q: 28. What is optional chaining? 
A: user?.address?.city - returns undefined instead of throwing if any part is null/undefined. Works with 
methods: obj.method?.() and arrays: arr?.[0]. 
Q: 29. What is nullish coalescing? 
A: ?? returns right side only when left is null/undefined. Unlike ||, it doesn't treat 0, false, '' as falsy. x ?? 
'default'. 
Q: 30. What is the difference between map, filter, reduce? 
A: map: transforms each element, returns same length array. filter: returns elements passing test. 
reduce: accumulates to single value. All return new arrays (non-mutating). 
