PART D: Advanced JS Concepts (Q101–Q150) 
Q: 51. What is the difference between synchronous and asynchronous code? 
A: Synchronous: executes line by line, blocks further execution. Asynchronous: doesn't block—
schedules work to be done later (callbacks, promises, async/await). 
Q: 52. Explain event bubbling and capturing. 
A: Bubbling: event fires on target, then bubbles up to ancestors. Capturing: event fires from root down 
to target. Use addEventListener(event, fn, true) for capture phase. stopPropagation() stops bubbling. 
Q: 53. What is the difference between forEach, map, and for...of? 
A: forEach: iterates, returns undefined, can't break. map: returns new array. for...of: works on iterables, 
can use break/continue. for...of is most flexible. 
Q: 54. How does JavaScript handle memory management? 
A: Uses garbage collection (mark-and-sweep). Objects with no references are collected. Closures, 
global variables, detached DOM nodes can cause memory leaks. 
Q: 55. What is a pure function? 
A: Returns same output for same input, has no side effects (doesn't modify external state). fn(a, b) { 
return a + b } is pure. fn(a) { count++ } is impure. 
Q: 56. What is the difference between Object.keys(), values(), entries()? 
A: keys(): ['name','age']. values(): ['John',25]. entries(): [['name','John'],['age',25]]. All return arrays, work 
on own enumerable properties. 
Q: 57. What is IIFE? 
A: Immediately Invoked Function Expression: (function() { ... })(). Runs immediately, creates private 
scope, avoids polluting global namespace. Common before modules. 
Q: 58. What is the module pattern? 
A: const module = (function() { let private = 0; return { get: () => private, inc: () => ++private }; })(); 
Exposes public API while hiding private state. 
Q: 59. How do ES6 modules differ from CommonJS? 
A: ES6: import/export (static, tree-shakeable, async loading). CommonJS: require/module.exports 
(dynamic, synchronous, Node.js default). ES6 modules are the standard. 
Q: 60. What is the 'new' keyword? 
A: 1) Creates empty object. 2) Sets prototype to constructor.prototype. 3) Binds this to new object. 4) 
Returns the object (unless constructor returns object explicitly). 
