PART A: Core React Concepts (Q1–Q40) 
Q: 1. What is React? 
A: React is a declarative, component-based JavaScript library by Meta for building UIs. Uses Virtual 
DOM for efficient re-rendering, unidirectional data flow. 
Q: 2. What is JSX? 
A: JSX (JavaScript XML) is syntax extension allowing HTML-like code in JS. Babel compiles it to 
React.createElement() calls. Must have single root element or Fragment. 
Q: 3. What is the Virtual DOM? 
A: A lightweight JavaScript object copy of the real DOM. React diffs new vs old VDOM (reconciliation) 
and only updates changed parts in the real DOM (batched updates). 
Q: 4. What are components? 
A: Reusable UI building blocks. Function components (modern, hooks) or Class components (older). 
Each manages its own state and renders JSX. 
Q: 5. What are props? 
A: Read-only data passed from parent to child. Props flow down (unidirectional). Children can't modify 
props. Accessed via function params: function Btn({label, onClick}). 
Q: 6. What is state? 
A: Local mutable data managed within a component. Changes trigger re-render. Use useState hook: 
const [count, setCount] = useState(0). Never mutate directly. 
Q: 7. What are React Hooks? 
A: Functions letting functional components use React features. useState (state), useEffect (side 
effects), useContext (context), useRef (refs), useMemo, useCallback, useReducer. 
Q: 8. What is useEffect? 
A: Runs side effects after render. useEffect(() => { /* effect */ return () => { /* cleanup */ }; }, [deps]). 
Empty deps []: run once. No deps: run every render. 
Q: 9. What is useState? 
A: const [state, setState] = useState(initialValue). setState triggers re-render. For objects/arrays, 
spread to avoid mutation: setState({...state, key: value}). 
Q: 10. What is the difference between controlled and uncontrolled components? 
A: Controlled: form data managed by React state (value + onChange). Uncontrolled: DOM manages 
data, accessed via useRef. Controlled preferred for validation. 
Q: 11. What is useRef? 
A: Returns mutable ref object {current: initial}. Persists across renders without causing re-render. Uses: 
DOM access, storing previous values, timeout IDs. 
Q: 12. What is useMemo? 
A: const memoized = useMemo(() => expensiveCalc(a, b), [a, b]). Memoizes computed value, 
recomputes only when deps change. Avoids expensive recalculations. 
Q: 13. What is useCallback? 
A: const memoFn = useCallback(() => fn(a, b), [a, b]). Memoizes function reference. Prevents child re
renders when passing callbacks as props. 
Q: 14. What is useContext? 
A: Reads value from React Context without prop drilling. const value = useContext(MyContext). Create: 
const MyContext = createContext(defaultValue). 
Q: 15. What is useReducer? 
A: const [state, dispatch] = useReducer(reducer, initialState). Alternative to useState for complex state 
logic. dispatch({type:'INCREMENT'}) → reducer handles. 
Q: 16. What is React.memo? 
A: Higher-order component: const Comp = React.memo(MyComp). Prevents re-render if props haven't 
changed. Shallow comparison. Pass custom comparator as 2nd arg. 
Q: 17. What are keys in React lists? 
A: Unique identifier for list items. Helps React identify which items changed/added/removed during 
reconciliation. Use stable IDs, never index (causes bugs with reordering). 
Q: 18. What is prop drilling? 
A: Passing props through many intermediate components that don't need them. Solutions: Context API, 
Redux, Zustand, or component composition. 
Q: 19. What is React Context? 
A: Way to share global data (theme, auth) without prop drilling. Provider wraps components; 
Consumer/useContext reads value. Re-renders all consumers on change. 
Q: 20. What is reconciliation? 
A: React's algorithm for diffing Virtual DOM trees. Assumptions: different element types = different tree, 
keys identify list items. Results in minimal DOM updates. 
Q: 21. What is lazy loading in React? 
A: const LazyComp = React.lazy(() => import('./Heavy')). Splits bundle, loads on demand. Must be 
wrapped in Suspense: <Suspense fallback={<Loader/>}>. 
Q: 22. What is React.Fragment? 
A: <React.Fragment> or shorthand <>...</> groups elements without extra DOM node. Avoids 
unnecessary div wrappers in DOM. 
Q: 23. What is the difference between useEffect and useLayoutEffect? 
A: useEffect: runs async after paint. useLayoutEffect: runs sync after DOM mutations, before paint. 
Use useLayoutEffect for DOM measurements to avoid flicker. 
Q: 24. What is custom hook? 
A: Function starting with 'use' that calls other hooks. Extracts reusable stateful logic: useFetch(url), 
useLocalStorage(key), useDebounce(value, delay). 
Q: 25. What are Higher Order Components (HOC)? 
A: Function that takes component, returns enhanced component: const Enhanced = 
withAuth(OriginalComp). Pattern for cross-cutting concerns. Largely replaced by hooks. 
Q: 26. What is the difference between React and React-DOM? 
A: React: core library (component, hooks, createElement). React-DOM: renders to browser DOM. 
Separation allows React to target multiple platforms (Native, etc). 
Q: 27. What is StrictMode? 
A: <React.StrictMode> enables extra checks in development: double-invokes renders to detect side 
effects, warns about deprecated APIs. No effect in production. 
Q: 28. What is error boundary? 
A: Class component with componentDidCatch/getDerivedStateFromError. Catches JS errors in child 
component tree, shows fallback UI. Hooks can't implement error boundaries. 
Q: 29. What is the difference between state and props? 
A: State: local, mutable, managed by component itself. Props: external, read-only, passed by parent. 
State changes trigger re-render; so do prop changes. 
Q: 30. How does React handle events? 
A: React uses SyntheticEvent wrapper (cross-browser). Events bubble up. Use onClick, onChange 
(camelCase). e.preventDefault(), e.stopPropagation() still work. 
