PART C: Advanced React Questions (Q71–Q100) 
Q: 36. What is React Router? Main components? 
A: Library for client-side routing. BrowserRouter: wraps app. Routes/Route: define paths. Link/NavLink: 
navigation. useNavigate: programmatic navigation. useParams: URL params. 
Q: 37. What is Redux? 
A: Predictable state container. Store (single source of truth) → Action → Reducer → new State. 
connect() or useSelector/useDispatch hooks. Good for large apps with shared state. 
Q: 38. Redux Toolkit vs plain Redux? 
A: RTK is official recommended approach. createSlice() auto-generates actions+reducers. 
configureStore() sets up middleware. Immer built-in allows 'mutating' syntax. 
Q: 39. What is React Query (TanStack Query)? 
A: Library for server state management. useQuery for fetching, useMutation for updates. Auto-caching, 
background refetching, stale-while-revalidate, loading/error states. 
Q: 40. Difference between Redux and Context? 
A: Context: built-in, good for low-frequency updates (auth, theme). Redux: external lib, DevTools, 
middleware (thunk/saga), optimized for frequent state changes. Don't mix them incorrectly. 
Q: 41. What are render props? 
A: Pattern: <DataFetcher render={(data) => <List data={data} />} />. Component receives function as 
prop and calls it with data. Now largely replaced by hooks. 
Q: 42. What is code splitting? 
A: Splitting JS bundle into chunks loaded on demand. React.lazy + Suspense for component-level 
splitting. react-router supports route-level splitting. Reduces initial load time. 
Q: 43. How to optimize React performance? 
A: React.memo, useMemo, useCallback for avoiding re-renders. Code splitting. Virtualization (react
window) for long lists. Avoid anonymous functions in JSX. Use production build. 
Q: 44. What is the React component lifecycle? 
A: Mount: constructor → render → componentDidMount (useEffect[]). Update: render → 
componentDidUpdate (useEffect[deps]). Unmount: componentWillUnmount (useEffect cleanup). 
Q: 45. What is Zustand? 
A: Lightweight state management library. const useStore = create(set => ({ count: 0, inc: () => set(s => 
({count: s.count+1})) })). Simpler than Redux, no boilerplate. 
