PART A: Core Node.js Concepts (Q1–Q50) 
Q: 1. What is Node.js? 
A: Node.js is a server-side JavaScript runtime built on V8 engine. Uses event-driven, non-blocking I/O 
model. Single-threaded but handles concurrency via event loop and libuv. 
Q: 2. What is the event loop in Node.js? 
A: Phases: timers (setTimeout/setInterval) → pending callbacks → idle/prepare → poll (I/O) → check 
(setImmediate) → close callbacks. Microtasks (Promise, process.nextTick) run between phases. 
Q: 3. What is npm? 
A: Node Package Manager. npm install, npm run, package.json (dependencies, scripts, version). 
package-lock.json locks exact versions. node_modules stores packages locally. 
Q: 4. What is CommonJS? 
A: Node's module system: const x = require('./module'); module.exports = x; Synchronous, cached after 
first require. ES modules (import/export) now supported with .mjs or 'type':'module'. 
Q: 5. What is process.env? 
A: Object containing environment variables. process.env.PORT, process.env.NODE_ENV. Use dotenv 
package to load from .env file. Never commit .env to git. 
Q: 6. What is a stream in Node.js? 
A: Data processed in chunks rather than all at once. Types: Readable (fs.createReadStream), Writable 
(fs.createWriteStream), Duplex, Transform. Memory efficient for large files. 
Q: 7. What is the Buffer class? 
A: Represents binary data (before ES6 TypedArray). Used for file I/O, network data. Buffer.from('hello'), 
buffer.toString('utf8'). Fixed-size raw memory. 
Q: 8. What is cluster module? 
A: Fork multiple worker processes (one per CPU core) sharing same port. Master process manages 
workers. Overcomes single-thread limitation for CPU-bound tasks. 
Q: 9. What is child_process module? 
A: Spawn child processes: exec (shell command, buffered), spawn (streaming), fork (Node script with 
IPC). exec('ls', callback) or const child = spawn('node', ['script.js']). 
Q: 10. What is EventEmitter? 
A: Core class for event-driven programming. emitter.on('event', fn) registers listener. 
emitter.emit('event', data) fires it. emitter.removeListener() removes. Extend for custom events. 
