Q: 1. What is JWT? 
A: JSON Web Token. Stateless authentication token: Header.Payload.Signature (Base64 encoded). 
Header: algo. Payload: claims (userId, role, exp). Signature: HMAC-SHA256 or RSA. 
Q: 2. JWT vs Session-based auth? 
A: Session: server stores session data (stateful). JWT: client stores token (stateless). JWT: scalable for 
microservices, no DB lookup per request. Session: easy revocation, smaller payload. 
Q: 3. What are JWT claims? 
A: Registered: iss (issuer), sub (subject), exp (expiration), iat (issued at), nbf (not before). Public: 
custom (userId, email). Private: app-specific. Payload is Base64—don't store secrets! 
Q: 4. How to refresh JWT tokens? 
A: Use short-lived access token (15min) + long-lived refresh token (7d). On access token expiry, client 
sends refresh token to /auth/refresh endpoint. Server validates and issues new access token. 
Q: 5. What is the difference between authentication and authorization? 
A: Authentication: proving identity (who are you?). Authorization: checking permissions (what can you 
do?). Authenticate first, then authorize based on role/permissions. 
Q: 6. What is bcrypt? 
A: Password hashing library. bcrypt.hash(password, 12) generates salt+hash. bcrypt.compare(input, 
stored) verifies. Slow by design (configurable rounds) to resist brute force. 
Q: 7. What is OAuth 2.0? 
A: Authorization protocol (not authentication). Flows: Authorization Code (web apps), Implicit, Client 
Credentials (server-server), Device. Used for 'Login with Google/GitHub'. OpenID Connect adds 
authentication layer. 
Q: 8. What is HTTPS and why important for auth? 
A: TLS/SSL encrypted HTTP. Prevents man-in-the-middle attacks, token theft. Always use HTTPS in 
production. JWT in Authorization header is exposed without HTTPS. 
Q: 9. Where to store JWT on client? 
A: Memory (React state): most secure, lost on refresh. HttpOnly cookie: safe from XSS, vulnerable to 
CSRF. localStorage: vulnerable to XSS. Recommendation: HttpOnly cookies with CSRF token. 
Q: 10. What are common auth vulnerabilities? 
A: SQL injection, XSS (steal tokens), CSRF, brute force (rate limit), JWT algorithm confusion (none 
alg), insecure direct object reference, session fixation. Always validate and sanitize input. 
